{"/service/ndnp/fu/batch_fu_immokalee_ver01/data/sn95047334/00529042474/1958040301/0199.xml":{"full_text":"God Prepares a Leader ILLUSTRATED SUNDAY SCHOOL LESSON \u25a0y AWrod J. Buescher\n-c.-tj.*.\u2014 F-~*\u2014\nAs Moses grew to manhood,\u2019he saw\nhow brutally his people were being\ntreated. One day, seeing an Egyptian\nbeating a Hebrew, Moses killed the\nman. Then he was forced to flee for\nhis life to Midian.\nMajor Canadian Events For 1958\nWL\n*<^\u25a0l\nVisitors to Canada this year\nWill find a multitude of major\n\u2022vents planned in towns, cities\nand populated sections all across\nthe country.\nFeature attractions will include\nthe Highland Games at Antigon-\nIsh, N. S.; the 300th anniversary\ncelebrations at the famous shrine\nat St. Anne de Beaupre, Que.; the\nCalgary Stampede, the Totem\nPole Golf Tournament at Jasper\nPark Lodge, Canadian Rockies, and\nthe Manitoba Provincial Exhibi\ntion a Brandon.\nApart from the host of other\nactivities planned for Quebec Pro\nvince, including the opening of\nthe fabulous new Queen Elizabeth\nHotel at Montreal, French-Canada\u2019s\ncapital city of Quebec will celebrate\n^^WASHINGTOIi\nL-.r. march of EVENTS\nBusiness Sag, Unemployment t Republican Leaders Worried\nRise Seen as Election Issues Upswing May Como Too Lato\nBy HENRY CATHCART\nCentral Press Washington Writer\nWASHINGTON\u2014 Both Democratic and Republican campaign\nstrategists have become convinced that the United States\nbusiness recession and mounting unemployment will become the big\nIssue of the 1958 congressional elections.\nGOP leaders are frankly worried about the impact of the eco\nnomic situation. They feel that even if the business outlook im\nproves later in the year, the upswing may come too late to offset\nbad effects on their party\u2019s popularity before the\nNovember balloting.\nOn the other hand, confidence of Democratic\npoliticians is increasing day-by-day. Even before\nthe sudden upsurge in unemployment in January,\nthey were confident they would be big winners in\nthe congressional battling. They now figure any\ndissatisfaction among the voters on joblessness\nand the business slump can be converted into\nmore seats.\nIn a sudden shift, the economic issue has com\npletely overshadowed the political controversy\nover who was responsible for America\u2019s lag in\nthe missile and satellite race with Russia. From\nNational Capitol a vote-getting standpoint, politicians are finding\na paycheck is more important than a sputnik.\nTherefore, there will be a lot of campaign oratory about jobs,\nages and living costs in the coming months as the issue snowballs.\nBoth parties feel that it is one issue that must be explained to the\nvoters. Congressional mail thus far indicates they are right in that\nbelief.\nSATELLITE SPAT\u2014Political observers in Washington are point\ning out that the Democratic advisory committee was caught by bad\ntiming again at their recent meeting when they issued a statement\nrapping the Eisenhower administration on the missile program just\nbefore the Explorer was shot aloft.\nMost politicos feel that it would have been wiser for the Demo\ncrats to have held their fire and to have softened their criticism of\nthe Eisenhower handling of the satellite program.\nIt was noteworthy that only 14 of 24 of the advisory council were\npresent to sign the harsh critique on missiles and among the miss\ning was the shrewdest Democrat of them all\u2014Harry S. Truman.\nAs it now stands, the successful satellite launching gave the Re\npublicans a staunch shot-in-the-arm and as an afterthought, Demo\ncratic strategists now privately acknowledge that \u201csilence might\nwell have been golden.\u201d\nVEEP To THE VEEP?\u2014Speculation is arising on who might\nbe the GOP running mate with Vice President Richard M. Nixon in\n1960 should he win the Republican presidential nomination.\nAs it stands now, there are two likely prospects\u2014one from the\nMidwest, the other from the East and both younger members of\nthe Eisenhower team.\nThe midwestemer is Interior Secretary Fred Seaton of Nebraska\nWho has won popularity and respect in Washington.\nThe easterner is Attorney General William P. Seaton,\nRogers of New York who has long been associated\npolitically with Nixon.\nPersonally, they are both close to Nixon and Prospects\nwould certainly be acceptable to him as running\nmates should he get the big GOP prize in 1960.\nA dark horse is Labor Secretary' James P. Mitchell of New Jer\nsey who has won respect f ro m both labor and management alike\nfor his handling of the Cabinet post.\nNixon still must win the nomination before the speculation be\n\u2022omes a matter of urgency, however.\nMoses wed a daughter of the priest\nof Midian. At he tended sheep on Mt,\nHoreb, God\u2019s voice came to him from\nthe midst of a burning bush, com\nmanding him to go back to Egypt\nto free his people.\nits 350th anniversary. There will\nbe year-round festivities in North\nAmerica\u2019s only walled city to\nhonor the great French explorer,\nSamuel de Champlain who erected\nthe first settlement in 1608.\nBritish Columbia, too, is cele\nbrating its 100th birthday in 1958,\nand every community in the Pro\nvince will share in the fun. One\nof the major attractions will be\nthe exhibit of the world\u2019s only\nmuseum train; a complete train\nwith equipment a century old re\nstored by the Canadian National\nRailways. A 150,000 Centennial\nOpen Golf Tournament at Van\ncouver from August 27 to Septem\nber 1 will be one of the highlights\nof the British Columbia celebra\ntion as will a visit from Her Royal\nHighness, Princess Margaret. FNS\nDijtiibuted\nMoses was reluctant to do the Lord\u2019s\ncommands, but finally consented. The\nLord commanded Aaron, Moses\u2019 broth\ner, to meet Moses in the wilderness.\nThe brothers met, and Moses told\nAaron of the Lord's plans.\nUnemployed Paid\n$99,671 In 1957\nReports Vocelle\nUnemployment Insurance pay\nments in Gadsden County to per\nsons who lost their jobs through\nno fault of their own last year\ntotalled $99,671. reports State\nIndustrial Commission Chair\nman James T. Vocelle.\nPayments statewide totalled\n$13,859,729, the greatest amount\npaid in a single year since this\ninsurance benefits program be\ngan in 1939. Workers file claims\nfor periods of unemployment at\nFlorida State Employment Ser\nvice offices over the State.\n\u201cWe believe this Unemploy\nment Insurance system of pro\nviding temporary income to eli\ngible persons who become un\nemployed through no fault of\ntheir own is one of the most ef\nfective safeguards our economy\nhas against recession,\u201d Vocelle\nsaid. \u201cOur operations policy is\nto pay benefits to anyone en\ntitled, and to deny benefits to\nanyone not entitled,\u201d he adds.\nThe program now covers 800,-\n000 employees of most Florida\nfirms with four or more work\ners. About three of every four\nworkers in non-farm employ\nment is covered.\n\u25a0Unemployment Insurance pro\nvides jobless workers with \u201ctide\nover\u201d income to bridge the gap\nbetween jobs. The most anyone\ncan draw in a single year in\nFlorida is $4BO, which is lower\nthan the amount paid in any\nother state except Arkansas.\nThe benefits extend for up to\n16 weeks in any 52 week period,\nbeginning with the date of filing\nthe first unemployment insur\nance claim, Vocelle said. The\nduration of benefits in Florida\nis less than in any other state,\nand the national average is $3O\na week for 26 weeks.\nThe benefits are paid from the\nState. Unemployment Insurance\nTrust Fund, to which all liable\nemployers contribute up to 2.9%\nof taxable payrolls on the first\n$3,000 wages of each worker in\na year. The Fund now has a\nbalance of $92,6 millions from\nwhich benefits to eligible job\nless workers are paid.\n\u2018Weekly benefit amount ranges\nfrom a minimum of $lO to a\nmaximum of $3O a week. To\nqualify for the maximum, a\nworker must have received\nwages totalling at least $958.76\nin his \u201cbase period.\u201d But this\nearnings sum would qualify him\nfor only eight weeks benefits. To\nqualify for the full sixteen\nweeks, he must have earned at\nleast sixteen times his weekly\nbenefit amount in the base per\niod. (The base period is the first\nfour quarters of the five quart\ners preceding the filing of a\nclaim.)\n\u201cThese unemployment insur\nance payments go largely into\nthe necessities of life and pour\nmoney back into the economy of\nthe community,\u201d Vocelle said.\n\u201cIn this way, they play a vital\nrole in helping to sustain pur\nchasing power when industries\nrelease workers and reduce pay\nrolls.\u201d\nModem Watch\nCleaning Device\nUsed By Wood\nW. L. Wood, Jeweler, says that\nhe has purchased a new ma\nchine, the L. R. Ultrasonic\nUnit, which is the very latest\nin watch cleaning.\nThis L. R.~ Ultrasonic Unit\nwas developed after a long per\niod of research and study and\nis designed to augment the time\nproven method of conventional\ncleaning with the new efficiency\nof ultrasonic, sound wave, ac\ntion.\nThe generator creates electric\nal energy to the transducer in\nsuch manner that when the\ntransducer is placed in proxim\nity with the solution used\" for\ncleaning, sound waves are pro\nduced.\nThe pitch or sound of the\nwaves is too high for the human\near to hear. Thus, the name ul\ntrasonic.\nThe action of the sound waves\nin the solution is such that ex\ntremely small bubbles, cavita\ntion, are created in the solution.\nThese small bubbles then im\nplode, explode inwards. The im\nplosion scrubs the dirt from\nthe parts to be cleaned.\nAction of the machine is suf\nficient for cleaning watches and\nsmall clocks, in much less time\ntha.i ordinary methods.\nIKE SENDS PICTURE TO BOY\nCarrollton, Ohio\u2014Donald Stine\nis a very proud and pleased five\nyear-old youngster these days.\nHis most treasured possession is\na picture of President and Mrs.\nEisenhower that was sent him\nby Ike.\nDcctores believe the boy is\nsuffering from leukemia (cancer\nof the blood).\nGADSDEN COUNTY TIMES, QUINCY, FLORIDA, THURSDAY, APRIL 3, 1958\nFam\nTHE OLD HOME TOWN By STANLEY\nLOOKS LIKE HES^ NO-HES FROM HOOTSTtoWN\nSA REAL RIP-SNORTZAJ/L HES TH CARETAKER OFTW'\nCOWPOKE RAISED'//HORSES ONTH'MERRY-dO-z\n#4 TH'SAMXE! 7 ROUNDS OF THAT CARNIVAL A\nX \\COMFANY W/NTERING OVB*\nTHERE\nJMh\nfc/ C ^L^r*** F/w zAy f \"'.J\n-J-f-t\n^7: staaju^.\n^t?-^~ON THE LOOSE/\nACCUSES SAUD OF ASSASSINATION PLOT- Gamal Abdel Nas\nser, president ot the new United Arab Republic, charges in\nDamascus. Syria, that King Saud of Saudi Arabia had plotted\nto kill him. He said that Lt CoL Abdel Hamid Serraj (right),\nSyrian Army strongman, had been given $5,320,000 to sabotage\nthe plane on which Nasser flew from Cairo. Serraj also linked\nKing Feisal of Iraq with the alleged plot (International)\n1958 AZALEA QUEEN AND RUNNERS-UP\u2014Miss Sara Joyce Hol\nlingsworth (center), 1958 Azalea Queen, is flanked by Miss Judith\nAnn Bradley, Lakeland entry (left), and Miss Gwen Jennings, Boca\nRaton. The three beauties were selected from a field of 16 in the\nAzalea Festival contest held in Palatka Ravine Gardens recently.\nThe Fernandina Junior Chamber of Commerce, who sponsored Mixa\nHollingsworth, will receive $250 in prize money.\nObviously nutrition is the subject being discussed by Homer\nE. Hooks, left, general manager ot the Florida Citrus Commis\nsion, and E. E. Kelley, Jr., president of the American Bakers\nAssociation. The two men, both residents of Lakeland, Fla.,\nare pictured at the recent National Food Conference in Wash\nington, D. C. Approximately 1,000 nutritionists, doctors and\ndietitians heard President Eisenhower and Vice President\nNixon discuss the importance of a well balanced diet to the\nnation's welfare.\nMoses and Aaron then called together\nthe Hebrew elders and told them all\nthe Lord had said and promised. The\nelders believed them and worshiped\nthe Lord.\nMEMORY VERSE\u2014Exodus 3:12..\nLET\u2019S PITCH IN!\nMen Behind Boys* Clubs\u2014An Inspiring Story Of Succes^\nOne of the past decade's most\nheart-warming and comparative*\nly unknown stories was revealed\ntoday with the announcement\nthat Boys' Clubs of America have\nreached a new peak in Clubs and\nmembership.\nThere are\nI now more than\n1 500 Boys\u2019\nI Clubs and\nI more than\nI 600,000 Boys\u2019\nI Clubs members\nI throughout the\nI country. This\nI representsan\nI increase of\nI more than 100\nI Mr Htir.\nyvi wub uui-\nHerbert Hoover ing the past\nten years.\nAnnouncement of this growth\nwas made by John M. Gleason,\ndirector of- the national youth\norganisation. Back of his an*\nnouncement lies a heart-warming\nstory of the men who have made\nand are making this growth pos\nsible.\nThe Boys* Clubs of America\norganization is headed by former\npresident Herbert Hoover, who\nhas served as chairman of the\nboard of directors for more than\n20 years. Under his leadership,\noutstanding leaders in every\nwalk of life have been gathered\ntogether to work for what Mr.\nHoover calls \u201cour most precious\nnatural resource our nation\u2019s\nyouth.\u201d\nThe movement owes its success,\nstates Mr. Hoover, to the quality\nof the leadership. Today there\nare approximately 10,000 Board\nmembers prominent in the bust-\nMrs. Joe Johnson\nClaimed by Death\nFuneral services for Mrs. Joe\nJohnson, 64, of Concord, were\nconducted by the Rev. Harold\nJohnson from the Concordia\nBaptist Church Tuesday after\nnoon at three o\u2019clock.\nBurial followed in Vickers\nCemetery with Butler-Morgan\nFuneral Home, of Quincy, in\ncharge of arrangements.\nMrs. Johnson, a lifelong resi\ndent of Concord, died in the\nGadsden County Hospital Sun\nday night. She was a member of\nthe Concordia Baptist Church.\nSurvivors include three sons\u2014\nElmo, of Concord, Willard, of\nChattahoochee, and Albert John\nson, of Tallahassee; three sis\nters\u2014 Mrs. Ella Hinson, Mrs.\nLottie Wood and Miss Edrie\nWalsh, all of Concord; five\nbrothers\u2014 Pasco and Norman,\nof Quincy, Bryant and Audry,\nof Havana, and Jim Walsh, of\nTallahassee; and four grand\nchildren.\nPallbearers were Francis Perk-\nTo All The Nice People We Know\non\nJR ..a time of\nhappiness\n\u2022'S ST Hr*dSmmA\u00ae/\ni b\nBest Wishes for a quiet\nand inspirational day!\nSTAFF PERSONNEL\nOF YOUR FRIENDLY PURINA STORE\nSUBER JOHNSON CO.\n215 W. JJ\u00abH\u00abr\u00bbon St. MAin 7-2341\nness and cultural activities of\ntheir communities who devote\ntime and energy to the operation\nand maintenance of local Clubs.\nAn additional 60,000 volunteers\ndonate special skills and services\nin connection with training pro\ngrams devoted to photography,\nprinting, art,\nI science, music,\nI sports, public\nI speaking and\nI the like.\nBehind this\nI local leader-\nI ship and back-\nI ing up the\nI present gener\nation of Boys\u2019\nClubs members\nS is a group of\nA*L.Cole outstand\ning men who\nconstitute tho organization\u2019s na\ntional loadership. In addition to\nMr. Hoover, these include Albert\nL. Cole, general manager of the\nReaders Digest, who actively\nserves as president of the Boys\u2019\nClubs organization; John M.\nGleason, an internationally\nknown authority on youth, who\nis national director, and a 90-\nmember Board of Directors,\nwhose roster reads like a digest\nof \u201cWho\u2019s Who In America.\u201d The\nofficers and Board also direct a\nnational professional staff with\nheadquarters in New York City,\na field staff and seven regional\noffices.\nTho roster of Boys\u2019 Club alum\nni affords striking evidence of\nthe value to our country of the\norganization\u2019s leadership, both\nnational and local. Among the\nthousands of outstanding gradu-\nins, Fred Strange, Joe Scott,\nLamar Durden, Randal Sadler,\nand Marvin McGill.\nREDS FEAR BAPTISTS\nLondon, England \u2014An article\nin \u201cKomsonoiskaja Pravada\u201d, an\norgan of the Communist youth\norganization, contains an odd\ncomplaint against Russian Bap\ntistsy. It says: \u201cThey are parti\ncularly dangerous, for among\nthem the laymen are evangelists.\nEvery Russian Baptist tries to\nwin at least one adherent to his\nfaith.\u201d\nLOST CASH SURVEY\nNew York \u2014Money may be\nharder to get now\u2014but it is still\nunfortunately, easy to lose.\nA survey by the American\nExpress Co., showed that U. S.\ncitizens reported losing more\nthan 100 million dollras in cash\nlast year, in most cases through\ncarelessness.\nAn interesting sidelight is the\nfact that this figure is sufficient\nto buy a Harvard education for\n10,000 students \u2014or to build a\ncommunity of 5,000 homes.\nPAGE THIRTEEN\nates are Irvin? Berlin, the late\nGeorge Gershwin, Representa\ntive Albert P. Morano, Conn.;\nthe Rt. Rev. Jeremiah Minihan.\n\u2666l* A A a*\nme Arcnaioeese oz\nm Boston; Dr.\nI Samuel A. Le\nvine, heart spe-\nI cialist;Vem C.\nRichards, Vico\nI Pres., Bank of\nI America.\nOthers aro\nJustice Fran\nds B. Condon,\nRhode Island\nSupreme Court\nand former U.\nJ. M. Gleason o. vongress\nman; Peter da\nAnna, artist who at 18 received a\nmurals commission from the gov\nernment, the youngest ever to ob\ntain this award; Leo Gorodetsky*\nviolinist with the Boston Sym\nphony Orchestra; Eddie Cantor*\nradio and screen star. Sport*\nstars who were members include\nJoe Di Maggio, former New York\nYankees hero; Jack Sharkey*\nformer world's heavyweight\nchampion, \"Albie\u201d Booth, Yale\nfootball star of the Twenties\nand John B. (Jack) Kelly, for\nmer single-scull champion of the\nworld, and father of \u2019\u2018Princess\u2019*\nGrace.\nFuture contributions of th*\nBoys\u2019 Clubs of America to our\nnation\u2019s leadership depend on the\ncontinuance of present standards\nof guidance. Further growth of\nthe organization will be in direct\nproportion to the number of vol\nunteer leaders who give their en\ncouragement and support t*\nBoys\u2019 Clubs.\nPier Angeli is wanted in Lon\ndon to play opposite Bob Mitch\num in \u201cThe Angry Hill,\u201d but be\nfore doing this, she\u2019ll probably\nwork in a trip to New York in\nbehalf of \u201cMerry Andrew,\u201d in\nwhich she co-stars with Danny\nKaye.\nELECTRICAL\nSERVICE\nAnything from wir\ning a house to replac\ning a light bulb\nIke Shepard\nat\nBELL-SHELFER\nFURNITURE CO.\nMAin 7-6543\nRes. MAin 7-3079","height":"29253","width":"20382"}}
